nternational presence in orthopaedic research that is based on a broad representation of the varied subspecialties within this surgical field for treatment of problems in infants adolescents middle aged and older individuals the goal of the orthopaedic research program is to develop fundamental knowledge to advance the treatment of musculoskeletal injuries and diseases our faculty members are dedicated to advancing the field with a focus on bench to bedside innovations through sponsored research the mentoring and development of stanford residents as potential clinical investigators widens this fundamental mission of the department we look forward to being able to provide enhanced orthopaedic care for our patients and to continue contributing to the global orthopaedic surgery knowledge base residency the goal of the orthopaedic residency program at stanford is to produce orthopaedic surgeons who are technically competent interested in the overall well being of their patients and knowledgeable of the literature in the field of orthopaedic surgery in addition we hope to stimulate interest in solving clinical and basic science problems in the field of orthopaedic surgery and have our residents become leaders in the field to accomplish this resident learning is stimulated by contact with patients and with questions from attending faculty members more services inside stanford medicine lacob family sports medicine stanford medicine magazine human performance lab orthopaedic surgery clinical trials you are here stanford medicine school of medicine departments orthopaedic surgery navigation for this section orthopaedic surgery home research education faculty contact us site navigation home arthritis and joint replacement foot and ankle hand and upper limb shoulder and elbow sports medicine spine trauma musculoskeletal tumor pediatric orthopaedic physical medicine and rehabilitation research education residency fellowship seminars faculty department faculty faculty openings c